## Vercel Web Analytics Installation Complete

I successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js App Router project.

### Changes Made

**Created/Modified Files:**
1. `package.json` - Added `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 as a dependency
2. `pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated with new dependency lockfile (created during installation)
3. `src/app/layout.tsx` - Integrated Analytics component

### Implementation Details

**Framework:** Next.js 16.2.1 with App Router

**Installation Steps:**
1. Fetched the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
2. Identified the project uses Next.js App Router (based on presence of `src/app/layout.tsx`)
3. Installed `@vercel/analytics` v2.0.1 using `pnpm add @vercel/analytics`
4. Added the Analytics component to the root layout file

**Code Changes in `src/app/layout.tsx`:**
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the body tag, after the children content
- This follows the official Next.js App Router pattern from Vercel's documentation

### Verification

✅ **Build:** Successfully built the project with `pnpm run build`
✅ **Linting:** No linting errors in modified files (existing errors in other files are pre-existing)
✅ **Package Manager:** All lock files updated correctly with pnpm

### Next Steps

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel project dashboard
3. Visit your deployed site to start collecting analytics data
4. Check browser Network tab for `/<unique-path>/view` requests to confirm tracking is active

The Analytics component will automatically track page views and web vitals data once deployed to Vercel's platform.
